<HEAD>Cardinal at Mass Says Letters Reflect Deep Racism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor says mail criticizing his
decision to set up a scholarship fund for blacks reflects
deep-seated racism.
   O'Connor read 10 letters from critics on Sunday in St. Patrick's
Cathedral at a packed Mass celebrating Black History Month.
   ``We may not realize it but deep in our consciousness there is
racism,'' the Roman Catholic Archbishop said.
   The letters ranged from threats to withhold financial support
from the church to anger to what one writer referred to as special
treatment for black people. O'Connor, 68, said he will answer each
letter.
   One writer accused O'Connor of ``stirring up racism.'' Someone
else suggested that the money should go to white people with large
families they are trying to put through parochial schools.
   O'Connor announced last month that he would donate his Social
Security checks _ $6,000 to $7,000 per year _ to the scholarship
fund.
