<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HomelandCoup     02-15 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeland Coup,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clergyman Charges `Reign of Terror' after Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of the
Bophuthatswana tribal homeland has ``unleashed a reign of terror''
since a coup attempt was crushed last week, a prominent clergyman
said Monday.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, general secretary of the South African
Council of Churches, said hundreds of people from the home area of
the coup leaders had been harassed or detained by soldiers of
Bophuthatswana and South Africa.
   South African troops put down the coup hours after rebel
soldiers in the nominally independent black territory seized its
president and several top officials Wednesday.
   Col. David George, police spokesman in Bophuthatswana, said 374
people had been detained in a continuing police operation.
   He would not comment on reports that most belonged to the
Progressive People's Party. Party leader Rocky Malebane-Metsing was
installed briefly as president during the 15-hour coup and remains
at large.
   The Star newspaper in Johannesburg quoted sources it did not
identify as saying five members of the homeland parliament from the
party were taken from their homes Thursday.
   The highest-ranking soldier in the rebellion, Warrant Officer
Timothy Phiri, and other alleged army rebels were charged with
treason, which carries the death penalty, the South African Press
Association reported.
   It said later that Phiri was not among the first 33 accused
soldiers, who appeared in magistrate's court Monday in Mmabatho,
capital of the homeland.
   Chikane said those detained included members and officials of
Malebane-Metsing's party abd people thought to have voted for it
last year.
   He said a crackdown could provoke ``massive resistance that may
result in a violent confrontation between the South African-backed
bantustan (homeland) forces and the people of Bophuthatswana.''
   Anti-apartheid activists condemn the homeland system as an
attempt by white authorities to divide and weaken the black
majority. About half South Africa's 26 million blacks live in the
10 tribal homelands.
   Bophuthatswana, with a population of 1.7 million people in seven
separate parcels of land, is one of four homelands South Africa has
designated as independent. They are not recognized abroad.
</TEXT>
