<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RigCount     02-15 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rig Count,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rig Count Falls By 18 To Total 968</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of oil and gas rigs working in the
United States dropped by 18 this week to total 968, Baker Hughes
announced.
   This week's total reflects the number of rigs working as of last
Friday. A year ago, the count 806, Baker Hughes said Monday.
   The previous week, the rig count had recovered from recent
losses by posting an increase of 22 to total 986. The rig count
usually declines during the first few months of the year.
   Houston-based Baker Hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number
of rigs actively exploring for oil, and not rigs producing oil. The
rig count is a widely-watched industry index of drilling activity.
   Hughes Tool Co., which merged this year with Baker International
Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept track of the number of working
rigs since 1940.
   In December 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the count
reached a peak with 4,500 active rigs. But in the summer of 1986,
the rig count fell to 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began compiling
figures _ as oil prices plunged to less than $10 per 42-gallon
barrel.
   Among the major oil producing states, California, Oklahoma and
Michigan each gained five rigs this week.
   Wyoming and Louisiana posted the largest decreases, losing 10
and seven respectively. Ohio and Kansas each lost five rigs, and
New Mexico and Texas each lost three. North Dakota's count was down
by two.
</TEXT>
